references: , we evaluate the effectiveness of VFLIP using five datasets: three image datasets (i.e., CIFAR10
), and one financial dataset (i.e., Bank Marketing (BM)

). CIFAR10 and CINIC10 have 10 classes consisting of 32x32 pixel images. Imagenette is a 10-class subset of the Imagenet dataset. Each image is resized by 224x224 pixels. NUS-WIDE has 81 classes with 634 image features and 1000 text features. We select the five classes following the previous study
. BM has two classes with 40 features.
. We validate VFLIP under a four-participant scenario with a single attacker and an eight-participant scenario with three attackers. Based on previous VFL studies
, the data features are vertically split among the participants. The optimization method is Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD). The bottom model architecture is VGG19

for the image datasets and a 4-layer fully connected network (FCN) for NUS-WIDE and BM. The top model uses a 3-layer FCN. The VFL training epoch is set to 50 for CIFAR10, CINIC10, Imagenette, and NUS-WIDE, and is set to 40 for BM.
. We evaluate VFLIP on two SOTA attacks: BadVFL
. The attacker without label knowledge conducts the label inference attack proposed by the previous study
. The attacker injects a backdoor trigger after
epoch. For the attacker without label knowledge, the poisoning budget is set to 10% and
is set to 20. For the attacker with label knowledge, the poisoning budget is set to 50% and
is set to 5. The attacker’s target label is set to 0. The details for attack settings are provided in
. To the best of our knowledge, there are no backdoor defenses specialized for VFL with split architecture. Following the previous study
, we apply the existing backdoor defenses designed for DNNs, such as Model Pruning (MP)
to defend against backdoor attacks in VFL and compare them with VFLIP. For applying BDT to the VFL scenario, we add noise to the embeddings following the previous study
is known for improving the robustness against backdoor attacks to some extent
, we analyze the ability of DP-SGD to defend against VFL backdoor attacks.

.
To find the defense hyperparameter for MP, ANP, and BDT in VFL, we explore various security-utility trade-off hyperparameters in a wide range like the previous study

, and report the results with the lowest ASR while maintaining accuracy. For MP, we vary the pruning ratios from 10% to 90%.
For ANP, similar to MP, we vary the ANP ratio from %0.1 to 2%.
For BDT, we increase the noise level until the accuracy is no longer maintained.
In the case of DP-SGD, we select the lowest

values among those showing stable model convergence: 6.35 for CIFAR10 and CINIC10, 4.65 for Imagenette and NUS-WIDE, and 8.84 for BM. The clipping value is determined based on the median of gradients’ magnitude when DP-SGD is not applied, as guided by the previous study
In VFLIP, the architecture of MAE employs a 3-layer FCN for both the encoder and the decoder. We set the learning rate of the "
" strategy’s learning rate to 0.1. For identification,

is set to 2 for CIFAR10, CINIC10, NUS-WIDE, and BM, and 2.5 for Imagenette. Dropout is set to 10%. The MAE training epoch is set to 20 for CIFAR10, CINIC10, NUS-WIDE, and BM, and it is set to 50 for Imagenette.

. We employ two metrics to assess the robustness of VFLIP: clean accuracy (ACC) and attack success rate (ASR). ACC is the probability of correctly predicting the true label in the absence of backdoor triggers. ASR represents the probability of the model misclassifying the labels of the backdoor-triggered samples as the attacker’s target label.
